Barack Obama will be the fourth American President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
American President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth American president of history.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will receive them, among other things, for the exceptional effort to strengthen global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive at the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and they will have a lot to do.
First, the visit of the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee who, in October, elected him from 172 people to 33 organizations.
The presidential couple will then have a meeting with the king of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive him, although the third to receive him in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will speak of the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the prize as President of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the check of 10 million Swedish kroner (approximately 24 million Czech kroner).
It is proposed to donate them to charitable paraphim, but it has not yet decided to which particular organization.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests will attend.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, the feeling that he did not deserve it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all who fight for the same values as he.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action."
