USA: Replay is the Mother of Wisdom · Global Voices
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the most intelligent man, as a diligent student, repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only in the same text is the "same as in Iraq" speech used several times, but also he did not hesitate to use the title of the Bush statement of January 2007 for his own statement: "A new way forward."
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, demonstrated that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today nothing is spoken of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but objectively left his successor a much more favourable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even in spite of the traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided gunmen in the White House to a hard criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general over 10,000 military.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself had previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing about Obama's whole strategy seems to be its goal, starting to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and ending this procedure in three years. Obama's whole doctrine generated more questions from the answers it offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, after which patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confused relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action," a minimum objective of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is plagued by its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon," will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will consider it an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, and do not want to explain to their electors, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: to try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each solution will be a dramatic setback to the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential elections are three years away and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
