This year women received the Nobel Prize in all categories but Physics
Five women, a record number, received the Nobel Prize this year in specialized categories and in literature in Stockholm today from King Charles XVI Gustavo of Sweden.
In addition to the four scientists, the award-winners also included a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was received by two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as his compatriot Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel in chemistry was received by the Israeli Ada Jonath and the Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for the explanation of the structure and function of the ribosomes.
The last prize, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was received by American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without an award-winning woman, was Physics.
This award was received today by scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the RCD chip, which is the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each award was awarded the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of the money received.
This sum in each category is up to 10 million Swedish kroner (approximately 25 million Czech kroner).
In the case of several awards in each category, the award is shared with each other.
The traditionally most expected Nobel, the Peace, received it this afternoon in Oslo, Norway, American President Barack Obama.
