Hyundai met the requirements of the trade unions. It will cancel all additional work
The management of the car factory in Nošovice agreed with the unions to cancel all additional work.
It was precisely because of the frequent additional work that the trade unions declared on Monday the strike emergency.
The information was confirmed by Petr Vaněk, the spokesman for the Hyundai automotive factory.
The management, however, wants for this year to agree with the unions one more Saturday shift.
"We cannot resign to our manufacturing plan, as it is essential. That is why we proposed voluntary additional work for Saturday, December 19, that is, it will work in two shifts," Vanděk said.
According to the Sedmička.cz server, the company offered a bonus of 400 CZK to employees working the Saturday shift.
The bonus will also be paid for last Saturday, November 28.
According to Vaňka, the company decided to change the way its employees are motivated by the additional work offered.
Employees can charge the bonus for overtime or they can take a day off on December 28, that is to say, prolong in one day the Christmas parties, said Vaněk.
In addition, all employees on Saturday's shifts will receive money for the trip and for the food.
Because the additional work was the most urgent and problematic point of the comments and complaints of trade unionists and strikers, who stopped manufacturing last week, the address yesterday afternoon immediately decided to cancel all the additional work for December, said Vaněk.
The employees of the car factory were forced to work two more hours in addition to eight-hour shifts and this situation lasted almost every day until last week.
After signing the agreement, the trade unions will cancel the strike emergency.
Another negotiation between the factory management and the trade unionists must take place on Monday morning.
The head of the Petr Kuchağ trade unions said on Wednesday, that if they committed themselves to meeting the requirements and signed the document, they are willing to cancel the strike emergency.
The situation at the car factory was aggravated last week, when approximately 400 employees spontaneously went on strike for frequent additional work.
They also protested against poor payment conditions and alleged harassment.
Management felt that employees had to work overtime to meet the requirements and be able to supply the cars.
The trade unionists in their statement of the strike emergency on Monday also demanded that none of the employees, who interrupted the manufacture last Wednesday, be penalized in any way.
As far as additional work is concerned, trade unions require the company to minimize it.
In addition, this year they require a remuneration of Kroner 5,000.
The car factory in Nošovice Hyundai currently has 2,000 employees.
Serial manufacturing was started last November.
Until last September it manufactured approximately 80,000 cars; its current production potential is 200,000 cars per year.
A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'encalled' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines already accessible.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, patients' lives may be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the virus replication is not completely deleted, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the medicines no longer work.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg shows the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that the substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way from all the medicines used today, and so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, "improved 'compounds, prepared to know the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are bound by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus
HIV proteasis is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV proteasis, there is no fractionation of the HIV virus and no mature and infectious corpuscules of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV proteasis, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective.
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV proteasis was performed as a test test, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the common enzyme variant is not as strong as in clinically used medicinal products, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, where the medicinal products often do not work.
The mechanism of the single effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications makes, that metalocarborans are interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective medicines against HIV, says Pavlína Đezáčová, the head of the laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of organic and biochemical chemistry and the Institute of molecular genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
