A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, took renewed attention on Friday with the dissemination of a document that provides for ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations that carry most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Prepared by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give to the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the overall temperature increase that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, a high representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as "the big picture."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions over the same period by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
On Friday, however, the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week was presented.
The United States Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected claims calling for mandatory cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking on a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did only two years ago.
The United States will not agree without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the US's top climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for having said earlier this week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global overheating.
With the future economic trajectory of the major powers of the world at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries of the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said that it was not surprising that the main powers were discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in seeking to contain the major emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change adviser for Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, even if most major participants say that the talks will at most produce political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States developed a proposal for a preliminary treaty of 24 pages early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who is leading international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government come to a close.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice-Minister, came down from the planes and ran to the Bella Center corridors, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, to be able to delimit the claims to be declared next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people come in and out of the convention center every day, the activists playing the guitar present night shows mocking the countries that they say are being sold, and preliminary proposals are being passed from hand to hand instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here at this time, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, Vice President for the global policy of Conservation International.
The heavy weights are coming.
