Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of the partners adhering to "values" determined from above as before to impose on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to the customer's preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially of R & amp; D and, even more so, of business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have a proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would be to put the collaborators at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire carried out by Orange among its employees, have an impact on the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
"In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!" B989
- Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory that American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of the executive commitment, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanical management position, unadapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the good functioning of modern companies means adopting a finalist view of human behaviour.
It is to integrate into all business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make part of its dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of the motivations of the employees.
The studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their image of the company, to assess what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of the mobilization factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate the management of human resources "in place."
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
