The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae had the same look as many other carnivores: a two-meter-long, 1.50-meter-high animal running on the two strong back legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been a special thing.
But the Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is unprecedented for the Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, a total of five specimens were collected.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the older fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the sauriums were divided into their three most important genealogical linings: the carnivores teropod (which include the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the sauropods quadrupeds known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivores (saurios with bird pelvis), to which they belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa Hallae's skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those that also possess the descendants of the teropod, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
In the case of Tawa Hallae also the bones of the spine were clearly partially air-filled.
Tawa is the theropod with the oldest and most primitive air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the subsequent giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers inferred that the sauries arose there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineage were separated in the beginning and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a unique terrestrial mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa found the remains of two other theropods not closely related.
The three cannot come down from a unique related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three waves of migration were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many fossils of dinosaurs continue to be preserved, while in other continents there is little to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their life space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of the current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other sauries.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship was extinguished at the limit of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
The successful stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It could have given a massive extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteor impact stops the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
