Ionic worlds
In a state of vigil, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts do the limits between imagination and reality fade.
As long as it happens during the dream, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unhindered ourselves to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, those who experience sleep-like states during the vigil, or see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are most often considered in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drugged.
Our imagination is our fault: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality to be blurred.
Onirically modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most different forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, insanity.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Era prophet Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and the psychosis and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neural substances of communication in the brain - especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholin - has been derailed and interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis very often complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts occur.
Gravity no longer has power over it.
The relationship between insanity and sleep has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a state of vigil, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great similarity of the state of madness with the oniric states," for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the dispurposes, wild formations, and miraculous of it."
It's the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and scandalously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it's floating near the roof of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red messes like blood, deformed, reclining their teeth.
They're chasing him, they kick him with heavy, flaming boots, they throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Strident and evil voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. starts two wires from the stereo, ties them to form a hanging knot, and sets them on a hook on the roof.
He goes up in a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump.
The rope is loose.
May it be a lesson to you, the voices in a chorus that bursts the eardrums, "go to the clinic and make them cure you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychosis, the last one two years ago, the first one almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was the LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, in addition to maniac-depressive, he takes medicines, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness, he's been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the interior, and fall into a state of overarousal that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecution mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the gates to a stream of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief doctor of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
Schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning addressed to it.
At the same time it enters into a passive role, as in a dream, it is overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
Paranoic thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distance from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still an unknown why our brain makes cabriolas.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to lose contact with reality on a provisional basis.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic provision for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neural maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains an unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which is also not manifested at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role - stress or traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a prior disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain's transmitting system.
When the brain heats up
The illogical of all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says the professor in psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
The perception of hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analysed the results in the book Die irale Welt in unserem Kopf (The Unreal World in Our Head), published last year.
The hallucinations are among the typical symptoms accompanying psychosis, but also, surprisingly, many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as personality limit disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and cranioencephalic trauma.
in a surprising way and under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also suffers from hallucinations.
