75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and work history of women in Spain', developed by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey carried out between 9,737 women aged 15-75 left no doubt about this: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the field of work due to maternity.
The study notes that there are many differences in the beginning of a couple and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, first start living together, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay living together and motherhood, and have less offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after the beginning of the cohabitation, which increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time of their life path to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a lot of influence on motherhood, but less on the timing of pairing, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they are married and when they have the first root.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which they are married and at which they have the first child.
The difference also remains between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average, respectively.
"Another division is established between women according to their level of education.
While those who have elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those at middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a child, "Delgado explains.
